                The function `shortest_paths` takes a `source` string and a `weight_by_edge` map of lists of strings to integers as input. It returns a map of strings to integers that represents the shortest path from the `source` node to every other node in the graph.

The function does not work correctly because it has a bug in the `for` loop that updates the weights of the nodes. The bug is that the loop should iterate over the keys of the `weight_by_edge` map, but it is iterating over the values instead.

Here is the corrected function:
```
public static Map<String, Integer> shortest_paths(String source, Map<List<String>, Integer> weight_by_edge) {
    Map<String, Integer> weight_by_node = new HashMap<String, Integer>();
    for (List<String> edge : weight_by_edge.keySet()) {
        weight_by_node.put(edge.get(1), INF);
        weight_by_node.put(edge.get(0), INF);
    }
    weight_by_node.put(source, 0);
    for (String node : weight_by_node.keySet()) {
        for (List<String> edge : weight_by_edge.keySet()) {
            int update_weight = Math.min(
                    weight_by_node.get(edge.get(0))
                            + weight_by_edge.get(edge),
                    weight_by_node.get(edge.get(1)));
            weight_by_node.put(node, update_weight);
        }
    }
    return weight_by_node;
}

